#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""Insert three annotated performance sequences after the Performance Decision Matrix."""
import sys
sys.stdout.reconfigure(encoding='utf-8')

SEQUENCES = """
Three Annotated Performance Sequences
Everything in this book converges on one moment: you, in a room, performing. The frameworks, the signal vocabulary, the compliance architecture, the authority design — none of it is abstract once you are standing in front of people. What follows are three complete performance sequences, annotated in real time, showing how the tools in this book operate together under actual performance conditions. Read them as you would a musical score: the performance and the theory running in parallel, each illuminating the other.

Sequence One: Strolling — Corporate Gala, 90-Second Set
Environment: 300-person black-tie corporate dinner, cocktail hour, round tables of eight. The room is already running. Music, conversation, servers moving. You are one element in a space that was not designed around you.

You are standing at the edge of the room before approaching any table. This is not hesitation — it is intelligence gathering. You run the 10-Second Scan from Chapter 7 across the room without making eye contact with any individual. You are looking at posture clusters, social hierarchy, who is facing outward, who is facing inward, where the energy concentrates. You identify a table of six where one woman is slightly turned toward the room rather than the group. Her posture is open. She makes eye contact with a passing server without any social calculation. She is already slightly outside the group dynamic. [Room-read: she is the most environmentally attuned person at the table — high VS category signal. She will notice you arriving before anyone else and give you your read on whether the table is ready.]

You approach with purpose, not urgency. You arrive at a pace that says you belong here and have been before. No pause at the edge of the table. No 'sorry to interrupt.' [Authority signal: certainty of movement. The limbic system reads hesitation at approach as doubt about belonging.] Before you speak, you take in three things: shoe positioning under the table (no crossed ankles, one person slightly angled away — that person will be least receptive), the dominant speaker (leaning forward, hands open, gestures outward — D-type, will want to be involved), and the woman you identified (already looking at you, slight smile beginning — Supporter type, will be your anchor).

You address the table directly. "You all look like the most interesting table in the room." A beat. "I mean that. Most tables have a theme. This one has actual weather." A small laugh moves through the group. [Technique: compliment the group first — from the strolling chapter. Lower resistance before the first ask. The observation about 'weather' is genuine — you read an energy variation in this group from across the room, and naming it creates an instant moment of being-seen.]

You address the D-type directly. "Quick question before I do anything — are you the one in this group who would be genuinely impossible to fool, or are you the one who secretly hopes someone can?" He smiles and leans back slightly. "Impossible to fool." [Challenger reframe — from the Volunteer chapter. You have just invited his skepticism into the performance as an asset rather than a liability. His conversion will carry the whole table.]

You do not immediately begin. You look at the woman to his right — your anchor. "And what about you?" She responds warmly. You hold brief eye contact and make a decision: she becomes your primary subject. [Volunteer selection in real time: Emotional-Supporter hybrid. Her reaction will be the room's permission slip.]

The effect runs. At the reveal, instead of watching the subject, you watch the D-type. His expression shifts — the managed blankness cracks into something he cannot quite compose back. [Tell Table, Red to Green: Challenger moving through skepticism into engagement. That shift is social proof for every person at the table and every table within sightline.]

Before he speaks, you take a half-step back. "I'll let you work that out." You make brief eye contact with the anchor, nod once, and move. [Strolling exit principle: leave on the reveal. The reaction that happens after you walk away is louder than the reaction you stay to manage.]

Sequence Two: Parlor — Private Dinner, Seated Group of 20
Environment: private dining room, twenty guests, long table, post-dinner. The audience is warm, social, slightly loose. The room has been together for three hours. The social hierarchy has already been established. You are performing in a room that has its own established weather.

You enter without announcement. The host has introduced you in advance; everyone knows something is coming. You let that prior context work. [Pre-show compliance architecture: the invitation was already set. The social contract to participate was signed before you walked in.]

Before speaking, you take four seconds to scan the table. You are looking for the room leader — the person others are checking after unexpected moments. Identify a man at the far end who is slightly angled to include both sides of the table. He is the one the room checks. [Room Leader First: from the strolling chapter. His engagement will set the room's permission level for everything that follows.]

You address him first. Not with the effect — with a genuine observation about the evening. You name something specific about the room, the company, the organization. His response is warm and direct. The table relaxes. You have been socially cleared. [Authority via endorsement: the room leader's engagement tells every other person that engaging with you is the right social move.]

"I'm going to spend the next twenty minutes with all of you. I want to be clear about what this is: I'm going to read you. Not trick you — read you. Some of what I say is going to be uncomfortably accurate. If it is, just let it land. You don't need to explain why it's right. I already know why."

A beat of silence. [Compliance framing: you have just told the room what the experience is, what to expect, and what to do with the accurate moments. You have pre-framed the desired response. The cortisol is slightly elevated — not threat, but anticipatory attention. The window is open.]

You begin with a group read — a behavioral observation about the room as a whole that is specific enough to feel personal and broad enough to land for everyone. "There are three kinds of people at this table right now. The first is thinking about something that happened this week that they haven't mentioned to anyone here. The second is the person who noticed something about someone else at this table tonight and chose not to say it. And the third is the person who already knows which one they are and is hoping I go in the other direction." [Warm reading structure: Barnum with behavioral specificity. The third category creates a loop that everyone enters, because everyone believes they know which category they're in.]

You work the room for twenty minutes. For each volunteer interaction, you run the recovery protocol silently if needed — if a specific read misses, you reframe at Level 1, move to Level 2 if necessary, and never announce the miss. [Recovery Protocol, Ch21: the four-level structure running invisibly beneath the surface of the performance. No one sees the framework. They see precision.]

You close with the room leader. The final effect involves him directly. His reaction — genuine, specific, unmanaged — is the room's closing signal. You do not explain what happened. You say one sentence that names what the room just experienced. Then you stop. [The closer design principle: the last thing you say should name the experience without describing the method. Give the room a sentence they will repeat at dinner next week.]

Sequence Three: Corporate Keynote — General Session, 400 People
Environment: annual company conference, general session, 400 people, hotel ballroom, 9am slot. The audience has just sat through thirty minutes of executive messaging. The room is half-awake. The coffee was not enough.

You begin before you are introduced.

During the speaker before you, you are backstage running the pre-show sequence. Your event contact has already identified three people for you from the pre-show conversation you had two days ago: the person who is most skeptical about this kind of work, the company's highest-status social connector, and the person who has an upcoming milestone that the room is aware of. You know their seats. You know which one leads. [Pre-show intelligence: from Ch21. The show is already running. The reading that will feel impossible in thirty minutes is based on information you gathered in a two-day-old phone call.]

You have also sent a pre-show email to the event planner with specific language for the introduction: not a bio, but a behavioral frame. The introduction does not describe what you do. It asks the audience a question. The room has been asked to prepare before they see you. [Pre-entry architecture: from the corporate chapter. The audience's cognitive state before you walk on is a variable you can design. Most performers leave it to chance.]

The introduction plays as video. You are watching the room on a monitor backstage. You see the posture shift that happens in the third sentence — the room comes online. People sit up. [FATE Model: you designed the F (focus) and A (authority) before entering. The room's T (tribe) is already set by the company context. You are adjusting E (emotion) as you watch.]

You walk on. No wave. No smile for the room yet. You walk to center stage and stop. Twelve seconds of silence. Every phone goes down. [Novelty + contrast: stillness after thirty minutes of slides and executive language is the strongest possible contrast signal. The salience network fires.]

"Someone in this room is thinking about a decision they haven't made yet. Not a small one." A pause. "I'll come back to that."

You move on immediately. [Unresolved uncertainty — Zeigarnik effect: the open loop is running in working memory for every person who recognized themselves in that statement, which is most of the room.]

The first effect runs with a pre-selected volunteer — your high-status social connector. Her reaction is genuine. The room reads her. [Room leader strategy: you have just borrowed her social authority. The room is now more permissive than it was before she laughed.]

Forty minutes in, you return to the opening statement. "I said someone in this room was thinking about a decision they hadn't made yet." You walk toward the section where your pre-identified skeptic is seated. "I'd like to talk to you." [Callback architecture: the open loop closes on the person who can make the resolution most powerful. The skeptic's conversion is not just a personal moment — it is 400 people watching the hardest sell in the room go over.]

The close names the experience. One sentence. Not a summary — a frame. Something the room will carry out of the ballroom. [The closer design principle, applied at scale: at 400 people, the frame you leave them with is the thing they tell the next person. Build it deliberately.]

You walk off the same way you walked on: without ceremony.

What All Three Share
Read the environment before you read any person. The room's behavioral state determines what the first move should be.

Identify the highest-leverage individual and earn their engagement first. Their compliance lowers the threshold for everyone around them.

Run the recovery protocol invisibly if anything misses. The audience does not know what you intended. Protect the frame.

Time the exit to the peak, not to your comfort. Leave them with the energy still rising.

Name the experience in the close. Give the room one sentence they can repeat. Make it specific enough to be memorable, simple enough to survive the ride home.

· · ·
"""

with open('manuscript-extracted.txt', encoding='utf-8') as f:
    content = f.read()

ANCHOR = ("The rule for all environments: observation is always the foundation. Every environment requires the behavioral reading layer to be running before anything else begins. The structure and timing change. The fundamental skill does not.\n"
          "Performer's Note\n"
          "I played a 400-person gala using the matrix row for intimate strolling. Wrong row, wrong show. The reveals were too personal for a room that size, the pacing was too slow, and the callbacks landed flat because half the room could not hear the original moment. I knew the matrix. I just did not use it. Now I sit down with the grid before every show and circle the row. That ten-second decision shapes every other choice: volunteer type, reveal depth, pacing, and where the callback lands. Do it before the lights come up, not after you realize you are in the wrong show.\n"
          "· · ·")

if ANCHOR in content:
    content = content.replace(
        ANCHOR,
        ("The rule for all environments: observation is always the foundation. Every environment requires the behavioral reading layer to be running before anything else begins. The structure and timing change. The fundamental skill does not.\n"
         "Performer's Note\n"
         "I played a 400-person gala using the matrix row for intimate strolling. Wrong row, wrong show. The reveals were too personal for a room that size, the pacing was too slow, and the callbacks landed flat because half the room could not hear the original moment. I knew the matrix. I just did not use it. Now I sit down with the grid before every show and circle the row. That ten-second decision shapes every other choice: volunteer type, reveal depth, pacing, and where the callback lands. Do it before the lights come up, not after you realize you are in the wrong show.\n"
         + SEQUENCES),
        1
    )
    print("Performance sequences inserted.")
else:
    print("ANCHOR NOT FOUND")
    idx = content.find("The rule for all environments: observation is always the foundation")
    if idx >= 0:
        print(f"Partial found at {idx}: {repr(content[idx:idx+150])}")

with open('manuscript-extracted.txt', 'w', encoding='utf-8') as f:
    f.write(content)
print("Done.")
